  <body>
    <header id="title">
      <h1>Don Buchla</h1>
        <p>Pioneer of Additive Synthesis and Musical Expression</p>
    </header>
    <main id="main">
      <div id="img-div">
        <img id="image" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/19/arts/19BUCHLA-obit/19BUCHLA-obit-superJumbo-v2.jpg?quality=75&auto=webp"/>
        <div id="img-caption"><p>Don Buchla, surrounded by several of his creations</p></div>
      </div>
      <div id="tribute-info">
        <p class="lifetime">Here's a time line of Don's life:</p>
        <div id="time-line">
        <ul>
          <li><p><span>1937 </span>- Born in South Gate, California.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1959 </span>- Graduated UC Berkeley, where he studied physics, physiology, and music. </p></li>
          <li><p><span>1962 </span>- Formed his electronic music equipment company, Buchla and Associates.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1963 </span>- Began designing his first modules for the Tape Music Center.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1965 </span>- Assembled his modules into the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System (later known as the Series 100).</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1966 </span>- Began selling commercially.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1969 </span>- Series 100 was briefly sold to CBS Musical Instruments.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1970 </span>- Release of the Buchla 200 series Electric Music Box.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1971 </span>- Created the Buchla Series 500, the first digitally controlled analog synthesizer.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1972 </span>- The Music Easel, a small, portable, all-in-one synthesizer was released.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1982 </span>- The Buchla 400, with a video display, was released.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1987 </span>- Release of the fully MIDI enabled Buchla 700.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>1990 </span>- Began designing alternative MIDI controllers, such as the Thunder, Lightning, and Marimba Lumina.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>2005 </span>- Lectured at the NIME-05 (5th International Conference on New Interfaces for Musical Expression), in Canada.</p></li>
          <li><p><span>2012 </span>- Buchla's intellectual property was acquired by Audio Supermarket, which started Buchla Electronic Musical Instruments (BEMI).</p></li>
          <li><p><span>2016 </span>- Died at the age of 79 due to complications from cancer.</p></li>
        </ul>

        </div>

      </div>
    
      <div class="fact-mag">If you have time, you should read more about this incredible inventor on 
      <a id="tribute-link"  href="https://www.factmag.com/2016/09/26/the-genius-of-don-buchla-suzanne-ciani-morton-subotnick-surgeon-alessandro-cortini/" target="_blank">Fact Magazine.<a/>
      </div>
    </main>
